hands_on_practices.solution:
We start from the differential equation for the neutron‐to‐proton ratio during the constant‐temperature phase:
$$\frac{dr}{dt}=\frac{\Gamma}{1+r_{eq}}\,(r_{eq}-r)(1+r)\,. \tag{1}$$
Here $r_{eq}=\exp(-Z)=e^{-\ln5}=1/5$ and the duration is $\Delta t=H^{-1}$ so that 
$$\Gamma\,\Delta t=\frac{\Gamma}{H}=\mathcal R=\ln3\,. \tag{2}$$

1.  Separate variables in (1):
$$\int\frac{dr}{(r_{eq}-r)(1+r)}
=\frac{\Gamma}{1+r_{eq}}\int dt\,. $$

2.  Use partial fractions:
$$\frac1{(r_{eq}-r)(1+r)}
=\frac1{1+r_{eq}}\Bigl(\frac1{r_{eq}-r}+\frac1{1+r}\Bigr)\,,$$
so that
$$\int\frac{dr}{(r_{eq}-r)(1+r)}
=\frac1{1+r_{eq}}\Bigl[-\ln|r_{eq}-r|+\ln(1+r)\Bigr]\,. $$

3.  Integrate from $t=0$ (with $r(0)=1$) to $t=\Delta t$ (with $r(\Delta t)=r_f$):
$$\frac{\ln\frac{1+r_f}{|r_{eq}-r_f|}-\ln\frac{1+1}{|r_{eq}-1|}}{1+r_{eq}}
=\frac{\Gamma\,\Delta t}{1+r_{eq}}
\;\Longrightarrow\;
\ln\frac{1+r_f}{r_f-r_{eq}}
=\ln\frac{2}{4/5}+\ln3
=\ln\frac{15}{2}\,. $$

4.  Solve for $r_f$:
$$\frac{1+r_f}{r_f-r_{eq}}=\frac{15}{2}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
2(1+r_f)=15(r_f-r_{eq})
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
r_f=\frac{2+15r_{eq}}{13}=\frac{2+15\,(1/5)}{13}=\frac{5}{13}\,. $$

Thus the final neutron‐to‐proton ratio is $r_f=5/13\,$.
